{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_babelfish_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656902/1921031001/0290.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAB,\nf With Sunday Morning Edition.\nWASHINGTON, D. U.\nrTHITBSDAY^.-.. March 10, 1921\nI THEODOBE W. NO YES. Editor\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\ntalxu 0?c?, llth St. and PennajlTanla Are.\nNew York Office: Tribune Building.\nCWctfo Office: First National Bank Building.\nKcropean Office: 3 Regent St., London, England.\nThe Evening Star, with the Sunday morning\nedition, is delivered by carriers within the city\nat 60 cents per month: daily only. 43 cents per\nBooth; Sunday only. 20 cents per month. Orders\nmay be sent by mail, or telephone Main\nBdOO. Collection is made by carriers at the\ndad of each month.\nBate by Mail?Payable in Advance.\nMaryland and Virginia.\nDally and Sunday..1 yr., $x.40; 1 mo., 70c\nDally only 1 j r.. $6.00; 1 mo.. 50c\nSunday only 1 yr.. $2.40; 1 mo., 20c\nAll Other States.\nDally and Sunday. 1 yr.. $10.00; 1 mo., $5c\nDaily only 1 yr., $7.00; 1 rao., 60c\nSunday only 1 yr., $3.00; 1 mo.. 25c\nRailroad Wage Reductions.\nFor some time past it has been expected\nthat railroad wages would be\nmaterially reduced. The railroads, it\nhj plain, have been running behind.\nIn the adjustment from war time to\npeace time and the transfer back to private\nmanagement the finances of the\nroads have not been balanced. Oper- j\nating expenses have exceeded in many c\ncases the income, in some cases the\ngross income. Business has fallen off\nto such a degree that hundreds of j\nthousands of cars are idle. This is a i\ntllCl. Lll'il Ul LliV 1 VIUUVV.U v. j\nproduction.\nIt has been recently said that if j\nthe railroads made full reports of their\ncondition many of them would so\ninto the hands of receivers. They\nare. it is believed, kept \"solvent\" only\nby a virtual moratorium on floating\ndebts.\nThe first step toward a general wage j\nreduction has been taken by the l'enn-1\nsylvania railroad, which has directed j\nits executive officers to give as carlv\nas possible proper notice that it is the j\nintention of the company \"to reduce\nthe salaries and wages of officers and I\nemployes to accord with economic con-\nditions.\" This order will affect every j\nperson in the system from the ^resi-1\ndent down, nearly 215.000 in all. ?*ther\nlines if if ovooof orl will folio.-j *his\nexample. The Xew York Central has\nplans ready for adoption that will, it\nis stated, rut off $500,000 a month from\nthe pay roll, chiefly through reductions\nof the executive and clerical compensations.\nThe attitude of organized *tbor\ntoward these reductions is a n 'sitter\nof keen public interest. Will these\nmen, the operatives, engineers, tire- j\nmen, conductors, brakemen, mainte-i\nnance of way workers and shopmen,\naccept the pay cuts involved in this i\nwholesale program of economy? If,\nthey do not a strike may come. And\nif a strike of the indicated proportions\ncomes the country will be in the grip\nof a most serious economic disaster,\nthe end of which cannot be 'oretold.\nThe present hope is thai the em-\nployes of railroads, executive, clerical\nand operative, will regard these wage\ncuts as a necessary part Of the general\nreadjustment that must come 1\neventually. If the economies are not\neffected the railroads will fail to meet\nj their fixed obligations. Floating debts\ncan be postponed and adjusted, but\nbonded indebtedness is not thus to be\nhandled, and receiverships are imminent\nin the case of some of the\n\"aoundest\" lines in the country. A\ngeneral railroad receivership would be\ndisastrous in its effect, not merely j\n1 upon the industries of the country, j\nbut upon the working forces. Ac-\nceptance of these wage cuts, which i\nare proportionate and affect all class-\nea of railroad workers from the ton i\n1\nl to the bottom, will make for speedier j,\nreturn of prosperity.\n\n1 I 4\nThe old-time eopybook including the\nline. \"Honesty is the best policy.\"\nmight be advantageously restored to j,\nuse as preliminary training for young I.\nmen entering upon business careers at\nmall salaries. The simple maxim i\nmight prevent an immature mind here!,\nand there from being misled by un-|,\nreasonable hopes of judicial sympathy, j\ni m\nEuropean statesmen who used to j\nadmit frankly that they were not in-1,\nterested in American political affairs\nhave recently applied themselves to\nthe subject with the most studious\nattention.\nA Herman statesman naturally feels\nthat his standing with the populace!\nI depends on the amount of opposition j\nhe can make to the payment of any\n4 kind of indemnity.\ni A Hieh-Pressure System Needed. 1\nSome years ago a plan was devised\ni and strongly urged for adoption to!\nI relieve the regular water service from\nI\n1 undue depletion in the fighting of fires i\nin the business section of Washing- j\nton. It was proposed to establish a\nhigh-pressure system supplied bv\nI pumps taking the water from the j\nriver. It was estimated that this\nwould eost about $100,000 for;\npumps and mains. The matter was\nseriously considered, but for \"economi\nleal\" reasons was postponed by Congress\nand Washington has continued\nto use for fire fighting purposes water\nfrom the Great Kalis dam, conduited\nto the reservoirs and sent through\nthe filtration plants into the mains.\nIn point of \"economy\" the filtering\ncosts of the water that has been used\nsince the high-pressure plan was\npigeonholed alone represent a heavy\nrate of interest upon the $100,000 for\nwhich the high-pressure system could\nhave been installed at the time of its\nproposal.\nit is now proposes, in connection i\nWith the increase in the water supply.\nto establish special mains for tire}\naerrice in order to Bain the maximum\nof pressure at the hydrant points, if j\nsuch mains are laid it would be far\nbetter to connect them with a river-1\nside pumping stating. which, takins1\nthe water directly from the stream,\ncould send it at an even higher pressure\nto the points of use.\nSince the high-pressure plan Was\nbroached costs have risen so greatly\nIn all lines that it is prnhable that the\nspecial fire pumping system would\nnot be installed now for less than five\ntunes the original estimate. This art\nJal a\ngument 'was repeatedly brought to\nbear upon the case while the highpressure\nplan was pending before Congress,\nand it was pointed out that the\ntruest economy would be the installation\nof the system at once, inasmuch\nas costs would certainly rise?though\nit was not then thought that they\nwould rise so high?and particularly\nas it was recognized that in a veryfew\nyears the regular water supply\nwould relatively fall to a point of dangerous\nmargin.\nThat point of dangerous margin has\nnow been reached, and a project is\nunder way for increasing the supply.\nIt is quite appropriate in connection\nwith the pending and it is to be hoped\nonly briefly postponed plan to urge\nagain the establishment of the special\nhigh-pressure system for the lighting\nof tires in the more congested parts\nof the city?the business area.\nThis matter has two aspects, first\nthat of the economy of the filtered\ndrinking water and second that of\nthe protection of the city. Washington\nhas never been visited with a\ngreat conflagration, and it is hoped\nthat it never will be. But there is no\nguarantee against it today. With the\nhigh-pressure fire service installed\ncovering the area of possible conflagration\nin the business section, the\narea occupied by the government\nbuildings as well as business establishments,\nWashington would be as\nwell protected against such a disaster\nas possible. The fact that no such\nfire has ever occurred here is no assurance\nof permanent immunity. The\nbest assurance is provision of plenty\nof water.\ni\nPorto Kico.\nThere is a movement in Porto Rico\nin favor of independence. It is difficult\nto understand why. The affairs\nof the island have been well administered\nby the United States. Im- j\nprovements of all sorts have marked 1\nAmerican control. Conditions were i\nbackward when we took charge. They l\nyre decidedly forward today, and like- j\n!y to continue in that direction while\nwe remain. I\nWe are increasing, not diminishing,,\nour interests in the West Indies. Since*\nacquiring Porto Rico from Spain we\nk.it-o ?u., A :_ 1..1 f 1\niic*,vt- atMuu cu iiic? xi ftiii loidiiun irum\nDenmark, anil improvements are in\nprogress there, according to recommendations\nmade by a congressional\ncommittee after an investigation.\nThe matter need not be too seriously\nconsidered, but the suggestion\nhas been made that Great Britain and\nFrance reduce their war indebted- j\nness to us by transferring their West j\nIndian possessions. The suggestion I\nshows that there is some sentiment in\nthis country in favor of raising the\nStars and Stripes over all the islands\nin that quarter.\nAs an independent country Porto\nRico could do nothing for herself\nthat we could not do better for her.\nShe is so small we should be obliged\nto stand by and give her the benefit\n3f our shield. We have quite enough\njf that sort of thing now in the case\n3f Cuba, where independence is not\nworking exactly like a charm, and\nwhere our watchful eye- is too often\nneeded.\nHome Sentiment and the Sessions.\nSenators and representatives will\nhave a month at home before assembling\nhere for work. In that time j\nthey can absorb the latest home senti-1\nment on the subject of the situation\nand what it calls for. The people have\nread and digested the inaugural message.\nIt has conveyed to them in\ngeneral terms Mr. Harding's inter?u\n\\r u? i i\nin ciaiiun vi mc ?>uvviuuri manuaie, j\nand they are advised as to how it i\nagrees, or differs, with their own.\nThe size of the November victory J\nwas a surprise everywhere. That the J\nrepublicans would win was the guess\njf nearly all trained political observers, j\nThat the winning would be of a substantial\ncharacter was the calculation\nof a smaller number. But it probably\noccurred to nobody that an avalanche\nwas approaching.\nBut an avalanche of republicanism\nswept over the country. Republican\nstates piled their majorities higher\nthan ever before. Close states slid\ninto the republican column with ease.\nEven in states unshakably demoi-ratic\nthe democratic vote showed a\nremarkable falling off.\nWhen the Congress chosen at that\nelection assembles for business the\nrei ublican power on Capitol Hill will\nbe greater than the party has ever\nexercised there: and on that account\nit must be exercised with all care.\nN'ext year the party must answer at\nthe polls for its legislative performances.\nand if the decision is adverse\nthe party will enter the ring in 1924\nwith a black eye.\nThe American farmer is still courageously\nendeavoring to secure the\nenormous yield necessary to meet the\nstatistics of grain transactions on the\nChicago Board of Trade.\nAfter exercising a personal supervision\nover the soviet assets, Benin is\ninclined to turn the glory over to\nTrotsky and let him struggle with the\nliabilities.\nIf all the historic books in contemplation\nare written a five-hundredfoot\nbookshelf will have to be designed.\nKerensky has managed to hold a\ngreat deal of influence in Russia for\nsome time without the assistance of\na press agent.\nRevenue.\nThe ways and means committee prepares\nrevenue measures, and after the\nHouse has acted, the Senate finance\ncommittee reviews the action taken\nand reports its action to the Senate.\nThis (rives great importance to those1\ncommittees, and assignments to them\nare inu'h coveted. They are badgesof\ndistinction.\nFinding revenue is not an easy task\nat any time. It is an exceedingly difficult\ntask at this time. The govern\nnient needs a (treat amount?far more\nthan ever before. The war has forced\nus to think in billions, and to raise\nanil spend billions.\nThe money must be found. Uncle\nSam must have his rations, and must\nJ\nt r i\npay cash down. His credit is good,\nbut he docs no business on tick.\nThis situation is causing Chairman\nFordney of the House and Chairman\nPenrose of the Senate to wear their\nthinking caps right along. Both have\nbeen in harness on Capitol Hill a\nlong time. Both have, participated in\nsome pretty difficult revenue contests,\nbut in none so difficult as the present\none.\nWhen the special session opens, the\nrevenue question will be put at once\nto the fore, and kept there until disposed\nof. The public interests demand\nthis. Business is on its toes.\nTaxpayers want to know their assessments.\nThe people will pay, but many\nmust make special arrangements to\ndo so, and they are entitled to every\nconsideration.\nComing, But Not Here.\nMiss Spring will lie in Washington\nwhen she arrives! She has sent many\nadvance notices that she means to be\nhere earlier in tho season than usual,\nand in honor of her coming, and with\nintent to give her a gay greeting, the\ngrass has turned green, the elms and\nmaples have put forth little leaves,\nthe cherry, pear and apple trees are\nputting on their embroidery of bloom\nand the bushes in the public parks and\nin the private back yards?lilac, forsythia,\nspirea and many other lovely\nthings are touching themselves up\nwith green. Pussy willows are waving\ntheir fuzzy tassels and hyacinths,\ntulips, crocuses, jonquils and all their\nbulbous friends are in a state of high\nexcitement and stand ready to break\nforth, if not in cheers, at least in\nbloom.\nAll the things that grow in tield and\nwood and garden are waking up, or\nare awake, because they have heard\nthe cheery song of coming Spring.\nThe fajr young lady is on her way,\nbut last night she stopped off somewhere\ndown in Southland. When the\nnews of her delay was carried to feeble\nand decrepit old Winter he cried out.\n\"Here is a chance for me to come\nback.\" and then he sent a message to\nPluvius to bring forth his rain tanks,\nand another message to North Wind\nto advance. He said to Rain and\nNorth Wind: \"Things look soft for us\nat Washington: the month of March\nis in control; she has a weakness for\nfiarebaeks and she will welcome Cold\nWind and Rain.\"\nThat is how it happened. But \"the\nconsensus of opinion is.\" and \"it is\nsaid by those close to the administration.\"\netc.. that merry, gracious Spring\nis on her way.\nThe idea advanced by Secretary\nHoovet of grouping related responsibilities\nin the government department\nbest equipped to meet them will be a\ndisappointment to the lovers of red\ntape as a form of official decoration.\nOptimism concerning the business\nof the world is expressed by Charles\nM. Schwab. All that is needed for\nrapid attainment of prosperity is for\nbig business men the world over to feel\njust that way about it.\nThe mere fact that Pancho Villa can\nbe kept from breaking into politics\nagain is an assurance that Mexican\naffairs are progressing safely and\nsanely.\nIt would be impossible for the\nHohenzollerns to escape the impression\nthat Ebert is not a very good\npresident.\nThere are still several weeks ahead\nduring which base r,all will be famous\nchiefly for its law a.v(- literature.\nGreat lawyers become great statesmen,\nand the rule often works the\nother way very satisfactorily.\nSHOOTING STABS.\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nSpring Fashion.\nSunshine smilin' \"Howdy do!\"?\nSnowstorm come a-streakin' through,\nSay in' \"Sunshine, clear the way!\nWinter's here and here to stay!\"\nVli.eiex ro kUL\nTf unci n uiuoici t agcu ou\nBlew the clouds clean from the sky,\nLeft the sunshine with a smile.\nSaying, \"Storms are out o' style.\"\nJud Tunkins says you can't always\ntell whether a man has a naturally\nbad disposition, or whether he is tryin'\nto make out his income tax return.\nA Discreet Forbearance.\n\"Hiram.\" said Mrs. Corntossel. \"you\ndon't talk politics as much as you\nused to.\"\n\"Nope.\" replied her husband, \"we've\nelected our public officials. Public officials\nare servants of the people an'\nmy experience is that when you've\ngot a good hand anxious to settle\ndown to work it's a bad plan to worry\nhim with idle conversation.\"\nAfter the Campaign.\nWith joy undiminished\nWe're toiling anew.\nThe heckling is finished.\nThe thinking is dye.\nBosses.\n\"Do you think,\" inquired Mr. Meekton,\n\"that a man ought to undertake\nto be a boss in his own home?\"\n\"Certainly not,\" replied Senator\nSorghum. \"A man who undertakes\nto be an uncompromising boss in his\nown home is pretty sure to find himself\nin embarrassments similar to\nthose of a statesman who tries to be\nbigger than his party.\"\nThe Thrifty Outlaw.\n\"Many bootleggers get rich.\"\n\"Ves.\" replied l.'ncle Bill Bottletop.\n\"The only complimentary thing you\ncan say about them is that they don't\nwaste their money hanging around\nand treating the crowd.\"\nA physician remarks that yeast\nwill cure many things, but not a\ngrouch. It might relieve a grouch if\nproperly mixed with malt and hops.\n?Baltimore Sun.\nThe impression is that Coolidge desires\nto shun the limelight. He has\nfot into the right place to escape it\nnow.?Omaha World-Herald.\nThe new sweet pea to be exhibited\nat the flower show next week is to\nhe named for the President's wife.\nObviously, a Harding annual.?New\nYork Tribune.\nEditorial Digest\nThe Passing' of Woodrow Wilson.\n\"When Gen. Smuts placed the name\nof Woodrow Wilson beside that of\nWashington and Lincoln on the roll\nof America's great, a large number\nof the newspapers of the country\nagreed with him. The majority, however,\nseem to hold with the Pittsburgh\nJtlspatch (Independent) that\nneither this \"idealised estimate\" nor\nthe \"denunciatory criticism of his\nmore rabid opponents\" will gauge the\nretired President's true place in history.\nMore democratic than republican\npapers, naturally, are vocal.\nTime must elapse before cool justice\ncan be done to this American\nPresident, whose work and aims\naraused so much of controversy and\nstirred such depths of partisan hatred.\nThe cotemporary mind must\ndisappear. Indeed, front the earth before\na true balance of judgment can\nbe reached concerning Woodrow Wilson.?Springfield\nRepublican (independent).\nWe aro glad to have had the use\nof his strength of egotism and will\nwhen it was needed. We are sorry for\nthe tendencies he has strengthened\nin a nation badly composed to be\nsubjected to them.?Chicago Tribune\n(independent republican).\nj- cms11 number\nlie is une 01 mc\nof groat mon who in groat times\nhave done great things, anil in the\nj history of the world war no figure\nj will be more commanding than\nj Wood row Wilson.?Philadelphia Record\n(independent democratic),\nj As the head of the nation during\nI a world war and as the champion of\nj an ideal of international peace to\nwhich the aspirations of the world\nI have rallied. Mr. Wilson has written\na record of success. He can await\nI the verdict of the future with equaj\nnimity.?New York Evening l'ost (inI\ndependent).\nNo other American has made so\nj much World history as Woodrow WilJ\nson. No other American has ever\n(tulked so large in the affairs of civilization\nor wielded so commanding\nj an influence in shaping their ends.?\nj New York World (democratic).\nHistory may say that he was not a\nsuccessful diplomat. But it Was his\nrare privilege to put in words as the\nj aspiration of America a principle\nwhich the world has accepted as its\nj standard.?Milwaukee Journal (inde!\npendent).\nj History will write Mr. Wilson down\nas one of the outstanding world figI\nures of all time.?Houston Post (dent\nI ocratic).\nHis experiences offer a much longer\nrecord of errors to be avoided than of\n[examples to be emulated. Hut it is\ndue to him to say that he earnestly\ni wished to make the world a better\ni place to live in.?Buffalo Express (inj\ndependent republican).\nWith the passing of the Wilson administration\nthere goes the noxious\ntheory that any man. however highly\nplaced, can speak for all of us at all\ntimes and places. There disappears\nthe idea that the President is somehow\nabove and beyond the people, instead\nof being their temporary agent,\ndirectly responsible to them.?Providence\nJournal (independent).\nHe stands with the most achieving\nof those who have served the world.?\nAtlanta Journal (democratic).\nYet we have faith to believe that\nbecause he was an idealist, because he\nfirst stood before men as a hampion\nof an internationalism that was sim|\npie Christianity, Wooi'ro/ Wilson's\nI fame will grow with the succeeding\nyears.?Chicago Post (itf'.ependent).\nOurs has been frn mean leader, hut\none whom far Ais'tant generations\nwill acclaim as among the best and\ntruest servitors of man.?Omaha\nWorld-Herald (independent).\nIf Weodrotv Wilson, like Lincoln,\nhad died shortly after re-election, his\nname would have gone down into history\nas that of a great and successful\nPresident.?Baltimore Sun (independent\ndemocratic!.\nWilson will stand out in that long\nperspective n? one who sought at\nleast to raise men higher, which is\ntrue greatness. Whether we like it or\nnot, whether we like him or not. the\nname of Woodrow Wilson will fill a\nlarge place in the records and in the\nthought of the future.?St. Louis\nGlobe-Democrat (republican).\nAny impartial study of the colossal\nfailure will show that it was due almost\nwholly to defects in the character\nor the temperament of the\nPresident.?Philadelphia North American\n(progressive).\nThe broad pages of the achievement\nstand. Woodrow Wilson has been a\ngreat President of the United States?\ngreat not only in spiritual purpose,\nbut in practical accomplishment\nHocnester limes-union v inucpruuent).\nHe was always the leaOer and his\nleadership was invariably toward the\nright. His faults were never those of\nintention and will soon be forgotten.\nHe becomes a citizen, but he will be\nAmerica's first citizen so long as he\nshall live. Nothing can wrest that\ndistinction from him.-:?Worcester\nPost (Independent democratic).\nIn creating this world-wide sentiment\nfor brotherly international co-.\noperation and pointing it toward a\ndefinite goal no other man has exerted\nan influence in any way comparable\nto that of Woodrow Wilson.?\nColumbus Dispatch (independent).\nHistory has a habit of pardoning\nfaults in men who have accomplished\nbig things. Probably it will be kinder\nto Woodrow Wilson than most Ameri-\ncans of his own time expect it to be.?\nCincinnati Times-Star (republican).\nWhether Mr. Wilson will take his\nplace among the great Presidents of\nthe nation it is too early to tell. Our\nown opinion is that he will, although\nwe do not believe that he will ever\nstand upon the same pedestal with i\nWashington. Lincoln, or even Roose-\nvelt.?Buffalo Commercial (independent).\nPossibly never in the history of the\nUnited States, certainly never since\nthe days of James Buchanan, has any I\nPresident retired from office so gen- i\nerally disliked a.nd so thoroughly dis- j\ncredited as Woodrow Wilson.?Kort\nWayne News and Sentinel (republican).\nWoodrow Wilson ranks with Bincoin\nand Wehster in the lofty utterance\nhe gave to the soul of America.\nHe expressed in words of glorious\ndistinction its reality as a land\nof dreams, of high purpose, of the\nbrotherhood of man. Yet he lost the J\nleadership of this nation more utterly\nthan any one who ever possessed\nit in such measure.?New York Mail\n(independent).\nHe has laid his contribution into\nthe exchequer of the common good\nanil has passed straightway into immortality.?Charlotte\n(N. C.) News\n(democratic).\nHe determined to have his own\nway with the world and make it j\nover, and the world, which has small\npatience with tyros, pushed him\naside as in the end it always pushes\naside those who get in its proper\nand natural pathway.?Detroit Free\nPress (independent).\nVnmiierprf with the might v who\nwrought for mankind.?Richmond\n(Va.) Newt. Deader (Independentdemocratic).\nIt is highly probable that historians\nwill be'less interested in his statements\nof principles than in the extent to which\nthose principles were put into effect.\nWhen his achievements are measured\nby that uncompromising yardstick it is\nnot at all likely that posterity will be\noverwhelmed with awe.?Rochester\nDemocrat and Chronicle (republican).\nHis ideals live, and when history deals\nwith Woodrow Wilson he will be given\na place among the great men the country\nhe loves so well, or the world, has\nproduced perhaps the greatest intellect\nthe I'nited States ever throned in the\npresidential chair.?Saginaw NewsCourier\n(independent).\nWilson Spent l.ast Evening Studying\nHills.?Headline. So did we.?\nArkansas Gazette.\n\"That's what I call giving something\nfor nothing.\" said the husband\nas he viewed Ills wife's new evening\ngown.?El l'aso Herald.\nA United States Treasury official\nsays there are millions hidden in the\nUnited States. Well, they can search\nus.?Springfield (Ohio) News.\nHardening would be more popular\nif one had a caddy to carry his spade,\nhoe and rake.?Jackson Citizen-Ratriot.\nV'/tttt ia fliA Hnm for William Utili.\nIenzollern to step out and crave the\nhonor of paying the first 10,080,000\nmarks.?Boston Herald.\n'i\nYEAR IN t^s *Q OA I Shavem I Buy Your\n:?dwisr<,nov:^t,;noois 30x3*72 yv#UU Cuticura Soap For\nwork of toot borne. TAINT JV&O/2 XT war XI For ???on?\nIT and prrwrre it. Snap them tip! TllG ISCW WaV For Lo?o:notlvo Knrtnoor\nInterior and exterior work. __ E For Eastern Star\nConanlt CMAS. t. MILLED, inc. J Without Mu(i I r JCTffiST\nFormer]/ MiJlrr Bro?.\" Aoto SupplJ L^????? And Man/ Mulch liml 1h UtM\nK FERGUSON, Inc. H2 14th St, 4 Door. North o.* H St ALPHE^r?>?, -w.\nFalallac Drpartaieat. PI, K. 231-23*\nH? w -*5fic HUB FURNITURE CO HIFj\nFurnish Ynnr Hnme With the Rest\nON CREDIT-?Weekly or Monthly Payments\nHousekeepers, Attention!\n4\n20-Piece Guaranteed Aluminum Outfit\n\ni >i r-? it r? r 7